<org.eclipse.epf.uma:TaskDescription xmi:version="2.0" xmlns:xmi="http://www.omg.org/XMI" xmlns:org.eclipse.epf.uma="http://www.eclipse.org/epf/uma/1.0.6/uma.ecore" xmlns:epf="http://www.eclipse.org/epf" epf:version="1.5.1" xmlns:rmc="http://www.ibm.com/rmc" rmc:version="7.5.1" xmi:id="-l2VGYQdrPOBM2TtPpaOsNw" name="gen_sys_reqs,_n1nkIEWMEd6Js4kKfkp_5Q" guid="-l2VGYQdrPOBM2TtPpaOsNw" changeDate="2009-10-08T11:16:43.671-0700" version="7.5.0">
  <mainDescription>&lt;p>&#xD;
    The main objective of this task is to ensure that the System Requirements are expressed in a formal, structured,&#xD;
    verifiable, unambiguous manner (this is the Engineering part of the process), to maximize the chance that the system to&#xD;
    be developed is exactly the system the Stakeholders need (asked for).&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    This is a definition of the solution to the problem, at the level of what the system has to do, rather than how it will&#xD;
    do it (which is design). It is likely that changes will be proposed during this task.&#xD;
&lt;/p></mainDescription>
  <sections xmi:id="_7iWeULQ2Ed6dub1WVMVYrA" name="Create structure for specification" guid="_7iWeULQ2Ed6dub1WVMVYrA">
    <sectionDescription>Decide what structure will be used for the System Requirements Specification. If you are not using an existing&#xD;
specification, then you should preferably follow a template or a previous specification as a starting point. Create the&#xD;
outline specification following the chosen structure. You may be adding to an existing specification, in which case the&#xD;
default would be to use that.</sectionDescription>
  </sections>
  <sections xmi:id="_XVP9gLQ3Ed6dub1WVMVYrA" name="Transform stakeholder requirements" guid="_XVP9gLQ3Ed6dub1WVMVYrA">
    <sectionDescription>&lt;p>&#xD;
    Review the Stakeholder Requirements Specification and Use-Case Model. Convert problem-oriented statements into&#xD;
    solution-oriented statements.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    For example, from:&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;blockquote dir=&quot;ltr&quot; style=&quot;MARGIN-RIGHT: 0px&quot;>&#xD;
    &lt;p>&#xD;
        &quot;The mechanic shall be able to update the EMS software.&quot;&#xD;
    &lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;/blockquote>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    To:&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;blockquote dir=&quot;ltr&quot; style=&quot;MARGIN-RIGHT: 0px&quot;>&#xD;
    &lt;p>&#xD;
        &quot;The EMS diagnostic equipment shall have a function for downloading a selected EMS software version onto the EMS&#xD;
        via the diagnostic interface.&quot;&#xD;
    &lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;/blockquote>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Constraints are often transferred without change. There may be many system requirements per stakeholder requirement -&#xD;
    and vice-versa.&#xD;
&lt;/p></sectionDescription>
  </sections>
  <sections xmi:id="_MMaLYLQ4Ed6dub1WVMVYrA" name="Generate interface control document" guid="_MMaLYLQ4Ed6dub1WVMVYrA">
    <sectionDescription>Review the Stakeholder Requirements Specification and Use-Case Model to identify external interfaces. Capture the&#xD;
specification of these interfaces in the Interface Control Document.</sectionDescription>
  </sections>
</org.eclipse.epf.uma:TaskDescription>
